&gt;&gt;Kent Mitchell wrote:
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;One other issue is that coverage (even path coverage) follows a
&gt;&gt;&gt;classic interpretation of &quot;paths&quot; being based on the structure of
&gt;&gt;&gt;the code.  But for an exception throwing language there is other
&gt;&gt;&gt;possible &quot;paths&quot; that are triggered by behavior of the called
&gt;&gt;&gt;code.  Consider:
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;public static void int parse (String s) {
&gt;&gt;&gt;  return Integer.parseInt(s);
&gt;&gt;&gt;}
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Classically this has exactly one code path and gets 100% coverage
&gt;&gt;&gt;if you pass in &quot;1234&quot; but behaviorally it has two paths because
&gt;&gt;&gt;parseInt can throw an exception.  So ... you really need &quot;data
&gt;&gt;&gt;coverage&quot; which is a nebulous concept to measure at best.
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;Kent
